Cancer Incidence in NHS Borders

#Loading the relevant libraries
library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(here)
#Reading in the cleaned data 
cancer_incidence <- read_csv(here("clean_data/cancer_incidence_clean.csv")) 

── Column specification ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
cols(
  id = col_double(),
  hb = col_character(),
  cancer_site = col_character(),
  sex = col_character(),
  year = col_double(),
  incidences_all_ages = col_double(),
  crude_rate = col_double(),
  crude_rate_lower95pc_confidence_interval = col_double(),
  crude_rate_upper95pc_confidence_interval = col_double(),
  easr = col_double(),
  easr_lower95pc_confidence_interval = col_double(),
  easr_upper95pc_confidence_interval = col_double(),
  standardised_incidence_ratio = col_double(),
  sir_lower95pc_confidence_interval = col_double(),
  sir_upper95pc_confidence_interval = col_double()
)
#Reading in the geography dataset
geo_codes <- read_csv(here("clean_data/geography_codes_and_labels_hb2014_01042019.csv")) %>% 
  clean_names()

── Column specification ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
cols(
  HB = col_character(),
  HBName = col_character(),
  HBDateEnacted = col_double(),
  HBDateArchived = col_double(),
  Country = col_character()
)
#The HB code for NHS borders is S08000016
#Merging the two datasets for reproducability in the future if looking at other areas
cancer_geo <- left_join(cancer_incidence, geo_codes, by = "hb")
#Cancer incidence specifically in NHS Border
cancer_incidence_border <- cancer_geo %>% 
  filter(hb == "S08000016") %>% 
  select(-hb, -hb_name, -hb_date_archived, -hb_date_enacted, -country)
#Generating a plot of cancer incidence over the years by sex
cancer_incidence_border %>% 
  filter(cancer_site == "All cancer types") %>% 
  filter(sex != "All") %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = year, y = incidences_all_ages, fill = sex) +
  geom_col() +
  facet_wrap(~sex) +
  theme_light() +
  labs(
    x = "Year",
    y = "Incidence All Ages",
    title = "Cancer Incidence by Gender in NHS Borders",
    subtitle = "1994 - 2018",
    fill = "Sex"
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(1995, 2000, 2005, 2010, 2015, 2020))

The incidence of cancer has increased overall from 1994 - 2018 for both males and females. However, the incidence of cancer is higher in females than males. However, in 2017, males had the highest incidence of cancer of all years where the figure surpassed 450 patients. As can be seen from the female graph, there is a spike in the incidence of cancer every three years.
